<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="26" type="diagnostic characters">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Diagnostic characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="26">
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Images of Nothovernonia purpurea (Sch. Bip. ex Walp.) H. Rob. and V. A. Funk A Habitat B Head before flowering with outer bracts tightly appressed C Fully flowering head showing well developed bracts D Head with only a few flowers but showing the well developed bracts. [Photographs by A. Thiombiano, M. Schmidt, and K. Schumann]" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9865" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Figure 3</figureCitation>
illustrates the habit of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Rob. &amp; V. A. Funk" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="H. Rob. &amp; V. A. Funk" baseAuthorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Nothovernonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Nothovernonia purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, note the large bracteoles at the base of the capitula. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Nothovernonia purpurea (Sch. Bip. ex Walp.) H. Rob. and V. A. Funk A head B involucral bract C floret with style branches D style branch with detail of sweeping hairs in square E longitudinal section of floret showing anthers F achene with pappus G achene H detail of achene setulae I examples of raphids from achene wall. [Illustration by Alice Tangerini (US)]" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9866" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Figure 4</figureCitation>
has the details of the capitula, note the stout hairs of the style branches (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Nothovernonia purpurea (Sch. Bip. ex Walp.) H. Rob. and V. A. Funk A head B involucral bract C floret with style branches D style branch with detail of sweeping hairs in square E longitudinal section of floret showing anthers F achene with pappus G achene H detail of achene setulae I examples of raphids from achene wall. [Illustration by Alice Tangerini (US)]" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9866" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
) and the setulae of the achenes that have pairs of cells fused together beyond the basal 1/3 (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Nothovernonia purpurea (Sch. Bip. ex Walp.) H. Rob. and V. A. Funk A head B involucral bract C floret with style branches D style branch with detail of sweeping hairs in square E longitudinal section of floret showing anthers F achene with pappus G achene H detail of achene setulae I examples of raphids from achene wall. [Illustration by Alice Tangerini (US)]" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/9866" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Fig. 4H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Rob. &amp; V. A. Funk" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="H. Rob. &amp; V. A. Funk" baseAuthorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Nothovernonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Nothovernonia purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has large, obvious foliiform bracteoles at the bases of the capitula, bracteoles that can often cover the involucre completely. In contrast, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Rob. &amp; V. A. Funk" authorityYear="2011" baseAuthorityName="H. Rob. &amp; V. A. Funk" baseAuthorityYear="2011" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Nothovernonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="amblyolepis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="26">Nothovernonia amblyolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has minute foliose bracts that are easily overlooked.
</paragraph>
